      modelAnswer: 'Haemoglobin is a globular protein with quaternary structure: four polypeptide subunits (two α and two β chains in adults), each containing a haem prosthetic group with an iron(II) ion that reversibly binds one O₂ molecule. Cooperative binding means that as the first O₂ binds, conformational change in the protein increases the affinity of the remaining sites; once one O₂ has bound, the next bind more readily. This produces the sigmoidal oxygen dissociation curve: at high partial pressures of O₂ (lungs), haemoglobin loads almost completely; at low partial pressures (respiring tissues), the steep middle section means a small drop in pO₂ leads to a large release of O₂. The Bohr effect describes the rightward shift of the dissociation curve when CO₂ concentration or H⁺ concentration is high. Actively respiring tissues produce CO₂, which combines with water (in red blood cells, catalysed by carbonic anhydrase) to form carbonic acid that dissociates into H⁺ and HCO₃⁻; H⁺ binds haemoglobin and reduces its affinity for O₂, so more O₂ is released exactly where it is needed most. Foetal haemoglobin (HbF) has a higher affinity, shifting the curve left, allowing the foetus to extract O₂ from maternal blood. Together, cooperativity and the Bohr effect mean haemoglobin loads efficiently in the lungs and unloads where O₂ demand is greatest.'
