      modelAnswer: 'All three are polymers of glucose joined by glycosidic bonds, but their structures differ in glucose isomer, bond type and branching, matching their roles. Starch (in plants) is a mix of amylose (long unbranched α-1,4 chains coiled into a helix) and amylopectin (α-1,4 chains with α-1,6 branches every 24–30 residues). The compact, helical, insoluble structure makes it an efficient energy store: it does not affect cell water potential, and the many free ends in amylopectin allow rapid hydrolysis when glucose is needed. Glycogen (in animals) is structurally similar to amylopectin but even more highly branched, giving a very compact, insoluble store with many ends; this matches the high metabolic rate of animal cells, which need to mobilise glucose rapidly during exercise. Cellulose (in plant cell walls) is a polymer of β-glucose; alternate units are inverted, producing straight chains that pack into microfibrils and macrofibrils joined by extensive hydrogen bonding. This gives high tensile strength, allowing the wall to resist turgor pressure, prevent lysis and support upright growth. Each polysaccharide is therefore a different solution to a different biological problem, despite sharing glucose as a building block.'
