      modelAnswer: 'The mammalian heart is a four-chambered double pump enclosed in the pericardium. Two thin-walled atria sit above two thick-walled ventricles. The right atrium receives deoxygenated blood from the venae cavae and passes it through the tricuspid valve into the right ventricle, which pumps it through the pulmonary valve to the lungs. The left atrium receives oxygenated blood from the pulmonary veins and passes it through the bicuspid (mitral) valve into the left ventricle, which pumps it through the aortic valve into the aorta. The left ventricular wall is much thicker than the right because it must generate enough pressure to push blood around the whole body, while the right side only pumps to nearby lungs at low pressure (which protects delicate alveolar capillaries). The cardiac cycle has three stages: atrial systole (atria contract, filling ventricles), ventricular systole (ventricles contract; AV valves close producing the first heart sound; semi-lunar valves open and blood is pumped out) and diastole (all chambers relax; semi-lunar valves close producing the second heart sound; atria fill from the veins). Coordination is myogenic. The sinoatrial (SA) node in the right atrium initiates each beat, depolarising the atria. Impulses are delayed at the atrioventricular (AV) node so that atria empty before ventricles contract, then conducted rapidly down the bundle of His and Purkyne fibres in the septum and ventricle walls, producing simultaneous contraction from the apex upwards. The medulla\'s cardiovascular centre adjusts rate via the autonomic nervous system; sympathetic input speeds it up and parasympathetic input (vagus nerve) slows it. Adrenaline and chemoreceptor/baroreceptor feedback fine-tune output to match demand.'
