      modelAnswer: 'Mammalian reproduction relies on the production and fusion of male and female gametes (sperm and ova) followed by development of the zygote into an embryo. Sperm are small, motile cells with a haploid nucleus, an acrosome containing hydrolytic enzymes for penetrating the egg, and many mitochondria packed in the midpiece to power the flagellum. Ova are much larger, non-motile, contain stores of nutrients in the cytoplasm and are surrounded by the zona pellucida and corona radiata. Both are produced by meiosis, which halves chromosome number and generates genetic variation by independent segregation and crossing over. After release at ovulation, an ovum waits in the fallopian tube while sperm migrate from the vagina, drawn by chemoattractants and aided by uterine contractions. On contact, an acrosome reaction releases enzymes that digest a path through the corona and zona; one sperm fuses with the egg membrane, triggering a cortical reaction that prevents polyspermy. Fertilisation restores diploid number and combines maternal and paternal alleles, creating a unique zygote. The zygote divides by mitosis as it travels to the uterus, forming a morula and then a blastocyst with an inner cell mass and trophoblast. Around day 7, the blastocyst implants in the uterine wall. The trophoblast develops into the placenta, an organ where maternal and foetal blood come into close (but separate) contact, allowing exchange of nutrients, gases and wastes. Embryonic stem cells in the inner cell mass differentiate into all body tissues, guided by gene-expression programmes and chemical signals. Hormones control the cycle: FSH and LH drive gametogenesis, oestrogen and progesterone prepare the uterus and maintain pregnancy, and hCG from the implanting embryo signals the corpus luteum to keep producing progesterone. Reproductive failure can occur at many points — gamete defects, fertilisation problems, chromosomal abnormalities, implantation failure or hormone imbalances — explaining why human fertility is relatively low compared with many other mammals.'
