      modelAnswer: 'Bacteria are single-celled prokaryotes with a peptidoglycan cell wall, a cytoplasm containing a single circular chromosome (often plus plasmids), 70S ribosomes, and a plasma membrane; they may have flagella, pili and capsules. They reproduce by binary fission: the chromosome replicates and the cell divides, allowing rapid growth (every 20 minutes in favourable conditions). Bacteria carry out their own metabolism and are alive by all definitions. Viruses are not cells: they consist of a protein capsid surrounding a genome of either DNA or RNA, often single-stranded; some animal viruses also have a lipid envelope studded with glycoproteins. Viruses cannot reproduce themselves — they must enter a host cell, hijack its machinery, replicate their genome, assemble new virions and release them, often killing the host cell (lytic cycle). Because of these differences, treatments differ markedly. Antibiotics target features unique to bacteria — for example, penicillin inhibits cell-wall synthesis, tetracycline blocks 70S ribosomes, fluoroquinolones inhibit DNA gyrase. They are ineffective against viruses, which have no cell wall, no ribosomes of their own and no metabolic processes to disrupt; using antibiotics against viral infections has no benefit and contributes to antibiotic resistance. Antiviral drugs are harder to develop because viruses use host machinery; they often target viral-specific enzymes (e.g. reverse transcriptase inhibitors for HIV, neuraminidase inhibitors for influenza) or interfere with viral entry/uncoating. Vaccines stimulate immunity to specific viruses (e.g. measles, polio, COVID) and many bacteria (e.g. tetanus, pertussis), and are the most effective form of prevention. Bacterial resistance is a major and growing threat from antibiotic overuse, while viral mutation rates lead to drug resistance and the need for updated vaccines. Hygiene, public health and surveillance remain crucial for both.'
